here at a glance are highlights of the 
third day of the republican national convention 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
george bush won the republican presidential nomination in a 
ceremonial roll call of the states his adopted state of texas put 
him over the top 
bush promised that he and newly minted running mate dan quayle 
would work like a couple of pit bulls to whip the democrats 
this fall 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
bush made the convention a family affair and he and his wife 
barbara were surrounded by their grandchildren as the republican 
national convention awarded him the partys presidential nomination 
their five children were delegates 
bush toured the superdome earlier wednesday checking out the 
podium and the teleprompter he will use thursday when he accepts 
the nomination 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
sen phil gramm lauded george bush as the greatest vice 
president this nation has ever had as he placed bushs name in 
nomination 
gramm the texan best known for the budgetcutting plan that 
bears his name described bush as a certifiable war hero committed 
to a strong defense on the other hand he said michael dukakis 
would wimp america and endanger peace 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
quayle at a joint news conference with bush was bombarded with 
questions about his wealth his military record and his private 
life 
he refused to divulge details of a 1980 florida vacation with 
washington lobbyist paula parkinson and he dismissed as a cheap 
shot any suggestions that he joined the national guard in 1969 in 
order to avoid going to vietnam 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
bush campaign aides revealed that the vice president had 
considered 12 people for a running mate 
they were sen bob dole and his wife former transportation 
secretary elizabeth dole new hampshire gov john sununu 
california gov george deukmejian south carolina gov carroll 
campbell gov jim thompson of illinois sens john danforth of 
missouri alan simpson of wyoming and pete domenici of new mexico 
and nancy kassebaum of kansas rep jack kemp attorney general 
richard thornburgh 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
delegates to the convention say bush should step out from 
president reagans shadow and come out of the chutes raising 
hell to capture the white house 
some delegates believe bush must sharpen his image to succeed 
with the advice ranging from declaring his independence from 
president reagan to using fewer hand gestures wearing hornrimmed 
glasses and standing straight others prefer that bush ignore the 
suggestions and be himself 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
