<TEXT>
a new study indicates that changes by the 
federal government and efforts by the blue cross and blue shield 
health insurance plans to contain hospital costs may be working 
according to the study released wednesday the private payers 
reduced their payments to hospitals by 48 billion over a 
threeyear period 
the study appears to counter claims made in 1983 when the 
federal government changed the way it reimbursed hospitals for 
medicare patients and experts predicted that would result in 
hospitals recouping losses from private insurors such as blue cross 
richard scheffler a california health economist who conducted 
the study covering the years 1983 to 1986 said hospitals tended 
to apply the guidelines set under medicares prospective payment 
system to their private patients as well 
it the prospective payment system ended up profoundly 
changing the overall operation of the hospital scheffler told a 
news conference 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
he said some of the savings realized by blue cross and blue 
shield plans resulted from medicaredriven changes at hospitals and 
some from the private insurorss own costcontainment strategies 
