labor leader cesar chavez plans to end his 
fast sunday at an outdoor mass at the united farm workers union 
compound in delano a spokeswoman announced today 
chavez 61 plans to end the fast aug 21 at an 11 am mass at 
the unions retirement village in this town about 150 miles north 
of los angeles union first vicepresident delores huerta said 
if chavez sustains his fast until sunday he will have gone 36 
days without food to protest the use of certain pesticides on 
california table grapes the fast began july 17 
dr fidel huerta chavezs physician repeated fears about 
chavezs condition and said he was unsure if chavez could sustain 
the fast until sunday said ufw spokeswoman lorena parlee 
cesars condition has deteriorated hes increasingly 
experiencing nausea vomiting and cramping dr huerta said 
chavez has dramatically cut back his activities and hasnt 
appeared in public since aug 11 because of his weakened condition 
he canceled a scheduled public appearance with the rev jesse 
jackson on sunday but allowed media to briefly photograph and 
observe a private meeting between the two in a small room at the 
unions retirement village 
dr huerta has been urging chavez for days to break the fast 
chavez has lost more than 27 pounds his body has consumed all of 
his fat deposits and now is burning muscle tissue doctors reported 
over the weekend 
all of his systems are being affected by the fast ms 
parlee said 
dr huerta and two other physicians have said the hunger strike 
could cause the possibility of irreversible damage to his 
health ms parlee said 
chavez launched this fast to protest use of five pesticides on 
table grapes and call attention to the unions boycott of 
california table grapes 
this is the longest fast by chavez who went 25 days without 
food during the 1968 grape boycott to recommit himself to 
nonviolence he conducted a 24day fast in 1972 to protest 
adoption of a righttowork law in arizona 
