<TEXT>
a federal jury has indicated it could be close 
to a verdict in a multimilliondollar lawsuit accusing the hunt 
brothers of attempting to corner the silver market 
the sixmember civil jury late wednesday notified us district 
judge morris e lasker that it had answered all but one of the 27 
questions it had to resolve in order to reach a verdict 
the panel began its fourth day of deliberations this morning 
the jury indicated in a note to lasker that it was stuck on the 
question dealing with the issue of damages to be awarded 
because the 11page verdict sheet requires the jury to make a 
finding of some antitrust civil racketeering or fraud violation 
before considering damages trial observers said that seemed to 
indicate the panel had voted in favor of minpeco sa on at least one 
of its allegations 
minpeco a mineral marketing company owned by the peruvian 
government is suing the hunts for 150 million and seeking treble 
damages under federal antitrust and civil racketeering statutes 
the trial began in february 
minpeco said nelson bunker hunt 62 william herbert hunt 59 
who also has extensive real estate holdings and lamar hunt 56 
owner of the national football leagues kansas city chiefs 
conspired unsuccessfully with several middle eastern businessmen to 
corner the world silver market 
minpeco said the hunts bought unusually large amounts of silver 
bullion in an alleged effort to manipulate world silver prices 
between 1979 and 1980 in the failed attempt to corner the market 
the hunts denied the allegations they said that unstable world 
political conditions drove up silver prices and that they suffered 
enormous losses when the silver market collapsed in march 1980 
