<TEXT>
the call by vice president salvador 
laurel for new presidential elections has attracted little support 
and is widely regarded as an attempt to revive his flagging 
political fortunes 
on aug 13 laurel accused president corazon aquino of 
incompetence and suggested both step down so an election could be 
held she has not responded but said at the time that he did not 
support her during coup attempts in 1986 and 1987 
the vice president has met with opposition leaders including 
sen juan ponce enrile and members of former president ferdinand 
marcos new society movement 
marcos was driven into exile in february 1986 by a 
civilianmilitary uprising that enrile his defense minister 
helped lead enrile also was mrs aquinos defense minister until 
she fired him last november after a coup attempt involving some of 
his followers 
enrile says laurel has been asked to lead a united opposition 
previous attempts at an opposition alliance have foundered over 
personal rivalries 
no major political figure has endorsed laurels proposal for 
elections several politicians who had criticized mrs aquino even 
rallied to her defense along with the nations two roman catholic 
cardinals and nearly all the press 
laurels elder brother sen sotero laurel declared his support 
for the president in a speech to the senate 
some commentators speculated the vice presidents announcement 
indicated a secret alliance between opposition politicians and 
military dissidents who sponsored several coup attempts against 
mrs aquino laurel denied it 
political observers said the tepid reaction measured the slide 
in laurels political fortunes since the mid1980s when he was 
among the bestknown opponents of marcos 
salvador laurel was born into a politically illustrious family 
and seemed to have a bright future in a country where family 
connections carry great weight 
his late father jose was president of the japanese puppet 
government in world war ii and his brother jose jr was speaker of 
the house of representatives before marcos abolished congress in 
1972 and governed by martial law 
critics say the vice presidents impatience poor political 
timing and clear presidential ambitions have been his undoing 
columnist luis teodoro a professor at the university of the 
philippines wrote in the manila standard one of the reasons for 
medias antagonism is the perception that laurel is unpopular with 
the public at large no other politician can arouse as much 
antagonism among ordinary folk 
sheila coronel wrote in her manila chronicle column i think 
that laurel deserves to be taken seriously and it is not 
because he represents the second highest office in the land he 
symbolizes something far more important the mindlessness and 
opportunism of our politics 
laurels decline began when he agreed to shelve his presidential 
ambitions and become mrs aquinos running mate in the february 
1986 presidential election he was under pressure from the 
influential catholic hierarchy which feared he could not unite the 
opposition 
both mrs aquino and marcos claimed victory in the election 
which was widely viewed as fraudulent the marcoscontrolled 
legislature declared him the winner but the uprising drove marcos 
from the country 
mrs aquino also named laurel prime minister but then abolished 
the office he was foreign secretary but resigned in september 
citing a lack of influence and fundamental differences with 
mrs aquino 
i feel like a member of a basketball team who is supposed to 
be the captain because i was supposed to be the prime minister 
originally laurel said but they never passed the ball to me 
they benched me and its already the fourth quarter and im still 
on the bench 
after that laurel made highly publicized visits to military 
camps encouraging soldiers to demand that communists be purged 
from the government 
he later claimed to have a secret intelligence report naming the 
alleged communists it turned out to be a list of public figures 
the military deemed liberal or leftleaning 
his nephew and protege benjamin laurel was defeated for 
governor of the family stronghold province batangas four months 
later several leading members of his united nationalist democratic 
organization including senate floor leader orlando mercado left 
the party for proaquino groups 
the rev joaquin bernas a jesuit university president and 
aquino adviser described laurel as the master miscalculator of 
philippine politics 
this misreading of the peoples pulse could mean that he will 
end his political career not with a bang but with a whimper 
bernas wrote in the manila chronicle 
