<TEXT>
stillwater national wildlife refuge becomes 
the nations second western hemisphere shorebird reserve this 
weekend but the honor may be a hollow one for the ailing swamp 
things are looking pretty bleak right now said norm saake 
a waterfowl biologist for the nevada department of wildlife he 
predicts that 80 percent of the marshes in the 164000acre refuge 
will be dried up by the end of the summer 
racked by backtoback drought years that have distilled the 
wetlands to a suffocating toxinridden stew the refuge 60 miles 
east of reno has become a murky grave to more than 7 million fish 
and 2000 birds in the past 18 months 
steve thompson a wildlife biologist at stillwater estimates 
the marsh areas will barely total 3000 acres by dedication time 
if were real lucky were getting down to the last ponds now 
after 1986 the most recent year of heavy precipitation 
stillwater swelled to 23628 acres of managed marshland thompson 
said by the following year it had dwindled to onethird of that 
and now after two abnormally dry years barely 4000 acres of 
marshes remain 
its just a shadow of what it was thompson said its 
been a tough year 
saturdays dedication will make the refuge the fourth western 
hemisphere shorebird reserve in north and south america and the 
second in this country according to laurie hunter of the national 
audubon society in new york the other us site is the delaware 
bay shoreline in new jersey and delaware 
the selection was made by the western hemisphere reserve 
network a conservation group made up of government and private 
agencies including the audubon society 
its quite an honor thompson said i think part of their 
reasoning was to draw some attention to the place its in dire 
straits 
stillwater is one of the last remnants of prehistoric lake 
lahontan which once covered all of western nevada most of the 
former lake bed shriveled long ago into dry sinks that fill up only 
during very wet years 
the refuge drew wide attention in february 1987 when the 
increasing salinity of its evaporating waters killed an estimated 7 
million fish in the carson sink one of several former lakes that 
comprise the refuge an unrelated outbreak of avian cholera killed 
about 1500 water birds 
since then the lakes have shrunk to ponds finally killing even 
the most salttolerant fish the water thats left in the carson 
river by the time it reaches stillwater is also polluted by 
agricultural runoff and natural elements from the soil like 
arsenic boron and mercury 
while the fish can withstand the toxic levels during highwater 
years the concentration of chemicals loss of oxygen and growth of 
algae become intolerable as the water evaporates 
its just poor quality water thats killing these fish 
thompson said 
the situation is worsening for birds as well as fish avian 
botulism has claimed 650 birds in recent weeks and scientists 
search the refuge daily looking for dead and dying birds to be 
burned or buried in an effort to keep the disease in check 
while scientists are concerned about the possible effects of the 
toxic water and disease on this falls migrating waterfowl saake 
said the dying wetlands could discourage birds from making their 
usual stop at stillwater along the pacific flyway 
we dont have enough water to keep them attracted here he 
said 
for migrating birds stillwater is a critical stepping stone 
in the 6000mile route between arctic breeding grounds and 
wintering areas in the southern united states and central and south 
america ms hunter said 
because it is one of the most important inland staging areas 
for migrating birds in north america stillwater has worldwide 
ecological value she said 
efforts to win more water for the refuge chiefly by acquiring 
carson river water rights are pending in congress one measure 
calling for a federal environmental protection agency study to 
determine whether treated sewage could be routed to stillwater has 
passed and is on president reagans desk 
another measure still in hearings would shift 12 million 
earmarked for flood control work to buying farmers water rights 
for the sanctuary 
sen chic hecht rnev calls both of his proposals a start 
on the long road back for stillwater 
between hechts work in washington and efforts by private 
environmental and wildlife groups saake said stillwaters current 
peril and saturdays dedication as a shorebird reserve may provide 
the attention that could save it 
theres finally light at the end of the tunnel just because 
its so bad he said 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

