<TEXT>
nearly 400 american and chinese psychiatrists are 
in beijing to trade ideas on mental health a discipline once 
regarded as irrelevant in the socialist wonderland of marx and mao 
this is very important to the development of chinese 
psychiatry said yang deson vice president of hunan medical 
university of the fourday conference this week on advances in 
psychiatry 
ninety percent of chinas top psychiatrists are here he 
said 
about 170 american psychiatrists from the american psychiatric 
association and more than 200 chinese are attending the seminar 
which takes up such topics as schizophrenia depression child and 
geriatric psychiatry and counselling patients with aids 
the chinese psychiatrists are presenting papers on such topics 
as drug abuse in beijing child mental health in conjunction with 
chinas onechild population policy and the use of traditional 
herbal medicine in treating chronic mental illness 
dr melvin sabshin medical director of the washingtonbased 
association said he was impressed with the quality of chinas 
epidemiological studies and the emergence of younger 
bettertrained psychiatrists 
sabshin who is making his sixth visit to china since 1978 said 
it was his impression that since the cultural revolution there 
has been more of an acceptance of psychiatry 
marxist ideologues have long regarded mental illness as an 
outgrowth of class oppression and dismissed psychoanalysis and 
counselling as bourgeois indulgence 
during the rabidly leftist 196676 cultural revolution the 
study of psychiatry was suspended and many psychiatrists were 
persecuted china now acknowledges that mental illness cant be 
treated with political dogma and has encouraged the study of 
mental health 
but according to yang china today has only 7000 
psychiatrists less than half of whom have graduated from 
fullcourse medical universities by comparison the united states 
with onefourth chinas 1 billion people has 35000 psychiatrists 
yang said older practitioners like himself who went to school 
before the cultural revolution were trained in soviet methodology 
although chinese now recognize the united states as leader in the 
field pavlovian theories of stimulus and response are still 
carefully studied 
very few chinese are trained in freudian psychoanalysis partly 
because of past political condemnation of freuds ideas on sex 
yang said 
chinese psychiatrists are also hampered by social attitudes 
toward the mentally disturbed yang said counselling is still 
regarded as shameful a stigma and most of his patients suffer 
from major psychoses that neighborhood committees the powerful 
community overseers responsible for settling social discord are 
unable to handle 
sabshin noted that this narrow definition of the psychiatrists 
role is prevalent throughout the third world he said he had often 
seen barefoot doctors dispersing medicine to people with 
anxiety depression or sexual problems while only those with 
permanently severe psychosis are sent to mental health 
specialists 
china has about 350 mental hospitals but only 100000 beds for 
an estimated 10 million people suffering from mental illness while 
there is no record as in the soviet union of confining political 
dissidents to mental hospitals chinas public security bureau has 
warned that the mentally ill are a growing source of crime and has 
set up 16 of its own asylums 
yang said mental problems in china such as emotional and 
personal conflicts family disharmony and sexual problems are 
similar to those in the united states one new element in china is 
mental illness related to business pressures and failures as china 
abandons socialist egalitarianism for marketoriented reforms yang 
said 
with young medical students still reluctant to pioneer work in 
chinese psychiatry its going to be very hard to meet the nations 
rising mental health needs he said china yang said needs 10 
times as many psychiatrists 
</TEXT>
