<TEXT>
strikes spreading through poland 
crippled production at five vital silesian coal mines thursday and 
paralyzed szczecins port and public transport opposition leaders 
said 
workers demand higher wages better working conditions and that 
the outlawed solidarity trade union federation be made legal again 
strikes that began tuesday when employees occupied the july 
manifesto mine near jastrzebie in southwestern poland spread to a 
fifth mine thursday 
transportation workers in szczecin also walked out joining a 
shutdown by dock workers in the nations secondlargest port the 
largest is gdansk home of solidarity leader lech walesa who 
expressed support thursday for the just struggle 
polands communist government which crushed and outlawed 
solidarity after imposing martial law in december 1981 declared 
the strikes illegal 
the law clearly states that a strike only can be proclaimed to 
defend economic and social interests of a given working group but 
it deems political strikes impermissible said the official news 
agency pap 
the latest labor unrest follows the pattern of five major 
strikes and 25 threats or brief work stoppages between april 25 and 
may 10 that constituted the worst labor unrest since martial law 
participants in those strikes also demanded legal status for 
solidarity 
workers at the jastrzebie mine at jastrzebie began a strike 
thursday according to mine director jerzy swiderski he said he 
did not know how many of the 8400 employees were involved but 
solidarity activists put the number at 1500 
about 600 bus drivers and other employees of szczecins 
municipal transport system stopped work thursday morning snarling 
public transportation 
witnesses said general cargo operations were said at a 
standstill on szczecins docks where solidarity spokesman wojciech 
maziarski said 2000 workers remained on strike 
in his first statement on the latest labor unrest walesa said 
i support the just struggle of the miners port workers and 
other strikers this is the only way to lead poland on the road to 
reforms the workers are defending solidarity because it is for 
them the key condition of preparing winning and carrying out 
economic and political reforms 
more than 2000 workers occupied the andaluzja coal mine in 
piekary slaskie on wednesday night mine officials and solidarity 
activists reported the andaluzja mine is 42 miles northeast of the 
four others now closed in silesia polands most industrialized 
region 
about 1000 workers at the moszczenica mine near jastrzebie also 
refused to pick up their tools wednesday night said adam 
kowalczyk a local solidarity leader the mine is one of polands 
largest employing about 11000 people 
police moved in thursday and sealed off the area witnesses said 
more than 400 miners remained on strike at the morcinek coal 
mine near the czech border they declared a sympathy strike 
wednesday with an estimated 5000 workers who have been holed up in 
the july manifesto mining complex near jastrzebie for three days 
strike leaders and management at july manifesto discussed 
creating an independent union that would not be called solidarity 
but no agreement was reached solidarity officials said 
no talks were held thursday according to mine officials and 
solidarity activists 
management and strikers said negotiations were at an impasse 
strikers want solidarity advisers allowed in the mine a demand 
management has refused 
czeslaw czerwiec a spokesman for the manifesto mine strikers 
said security forces hampered efforts by supporters and relatives 
to bring food to the mine 
were not getting enough to eat czerwiec said theyre 
making it tough for us 
he said miners would strike until their demands were met 
were fighting for everyone he said 
police on tuesday surrounded the july manifesto mine about 280 
miles southwest of warsaw after workers refused to pick up their 
tools about 9000 workers are employed at the mine which is key 
producer of highgrade export coal 
miners say wage demands were based on hardships caused by 
polands worsening economy which is strapped by a 60 percent 
inflation rate 
polands miners are paid nearly twice the national average of 
100 a month and receive extra benefits because of their role in 
the nations economy 
poland is the worlds fourthlargest exporter of coal and its 
mining operations are essential to the nations steel power and 
shipbuilding industries coal exports are also crucial because 
poland relies heavily on the sales to obtain hard currency to 
service its 39 billion foreign debt 
while workers continue to support the july manifesto strike 
there is no sign of widespread unrest of the kind that spawned the 
union eight years ago 
workers at the lenin shipyard in may declared a sympathy strike 
in support of steel workers in nowa huta who had shut down 
production there 
the solidarity commission in the lenin shipyard in gdansk has 
issued a call for workers to participate in a rally friday in 
support of the strikers 
