<TEXT>
an intentionally flawed space shuttle 
booster rocket performed successfully thursday in the last 
testfiring required before the resumption of manned us space 
flights officials said 
were ready to go launch alan mcdonald morton thiokol vice 
president for engineering said on examining the booster after the 
122second horizontal test 
the 20 million firing was a redundancy verification test to 
make sure the boosters new joints do what theyre supposed to 
contain superheated gases during launch the failure of the seals 
on one joint led to the explosion of shuttle challenger and the 
death of its sevenperson crew in 1986 
engineers deemed the test a success after preliminary inspection 
of the prone rocket if that evaluation holds and national 
aeronautics and space administration workers are able to plug a 
tiny fuel leak in the shuttle discovery the space agency will be 
able to set a firm date in late september or early october for the 
first shuttle launch in 32 months 
the fifth fullscale test of morton thiokols redesigned booster 
sent clouds of dust billowing thousands of feet in the air as some 
300 nasa and company observers cheered 
fantastic it looked really good this is it said john 
thirkill vice president of space operations for morton thiokol 
we have had no indication of any anomaly said royce 
mitchell solid rocket motor project manager at the marshall space 
center in huntsville ala it looks like just an absolutely great 
test from top to bottom the end of september is still within 
our sights 
morton thiokol and nasa engineers planned to begin tearing down 
the motor monday and expected final test results within two weeks 
said company spokesman rocky raab 
mcdonald said preliminary indications were that every safety 
feature intended to prevent leakage had worked and there was no 
immediate evidence of problems in any of the four flawed joints he 
said he believed the joints were the safest parts of the shuttle 
launch vehicle 
the hardware and the data will tell us this booster is ready 
to fly mitchell said 
with the 470 million redesign and motor testing morton thiokol 
has run five or six times the number of tests that were done prior 
to the first shuttle launch and in half the time he said 
david ewing the companys deputy director of program 
management called the redesign result very very robust weve 
put on the belt and suspenders and weve even added garters 
the test firing at morton thiokols test bay 25 miles west of 
here capped the companys 2year effort to revamp the rocket 
blamed for the january 1986 explosion that destroyed challenger 
killed its sevenmember crew and grounded the nations space 
program 
scores of improvements have been made to the 126footlong 
booster most related to reworking the field joints which hold 
together the rockets cylindrical segments 
the challenger explosion was blamed on a faulty joint that 
allowed a plume of superhot gas to burn through an oring seal and 
ignite the main liquid fuel tank 
for thursdays booster test two of the three field joints the 
casetonozzle joint and the ignitertocase joint were riddled 
with 14 flaws intended to test them to their limits as the rocket 
burned 11 million pounds of propellant the third joint was left 
unflawed as a comparison 
were demonstrating that the motor is so faulttolerant that 
even with flaws that deliberately circumvent all the safety factors 
that weve built in its still a safe motor raab said 
among the defects were separations in the bonded adhesive 
insulation that helps hold the joints together and channels cut 
with an exacto razor knife that would allow the fiery gas to reach 
the joints middle oring one of three designed to contain heat 
from the burning fuel 
the joints were equipped with heaters that maintain their 
temperatures at a minimum 75 degrees fahrenheit freezing 
temperatures the night before the doomed challenger launch were 
found to have contributed to the joints failure 
with the exception of the flaws the rocket is virtually 
identical to a productionquality version morton thiokol testfired 
june 14 and to the pair now attached to discovery 
the june 14 test said raab was an unequivocal success as 
were the three that preceded it in the past year thursdays test 
had been scheduled last month but was delayed when a worker 
overpressurized a joint causing slight damage that since has been 
repaired 
