<TEXT>
the united states syphilis rate last year was as 
bad as any since 1950 prompting federal health officials to call 
thursday for more emphasis on interviewing patients with venereal 
diseases and warning their sex partners 
final statistics for 1987 show 35241 cases of syphilis reported 
in the united states 146 per 100000 people equaling the 1982 
rate as the highest since 1950s rate of 167 the national centers 
for disease control reported 
reported us cases of syphilis have risen 30 percent in two 
years from 27143 or 115 per 100000 in 1985 the cdc said the 
number of cases in 1986 was not included in the report but was 
estimated at 28500 
the increase was greatest for blacks and hispanics 
groups for which incidence rates were already high the 
atlantabased agency said in its weekly report 
between 1986 and 1987 among americans 1564 the syphilis rate 
for black males rose 36 percent from 106 per 100000 people to 
145 the rate for black females shot up 43 percent from 56 per 
100000 to 79 
the rate for hispanic males rose 7 percent from 66 to 71 cases 
per 100000 while the rate for hispanic women rose 24 percent 
from 18 to 22 
in contrast the rate for white males dropped from 64 to 57 
cases per 100000 apparently due to a drop in syphilis among 
homosexual men and the rate for white females rose but still at 
small levels from 22 to 26 the cdc said 
previously reported drops in the sexually transmitted disease 
rates among homosexual men indicate changes in sexual behavior 
due to the spread of aids the cdc said 
the increases in incidence of syphilis suggest that 
efforts to achieve similar behavioral changes in minority 
populations have not been successful the agency said 
homosexual men have taken safe sex messages seriously 
said dr joel greenspan a cdc specialist in sexually transmitted 
diseases they have changed their behavior minority people and 
particularly heterosexuals have not gotten that message 
the increase in syphilis appears to be concentrated in a few 
urban areas 57 percent of all us cases last year were reported 
in florida california and new york 
in its report the cdc suggested several steps to curb the 
increase in syphilis including a move to reemphasize the 
traditional methods of syphilis control interviews and sex 
partner notification 
the agency also suggested screening for sexually transmitted 
diseases in highrisk populations assuring better access to 
medical care with speedy service and evening hours and further 
surveillance efforts to monitor the problem 
</TEXT>
