<TEXT>
when dan quayle enlisted in the national guard 
in 1969 the united states was faring poorly in vietnam volunteers 
for active military service were in short supply and the nations 
college campuses were awash in protest 
and short of becoming a draft dodger the guard looked pretty 
safe if you could get in 
during the war the united states sent 34 million servicemen 
and women to southeast asia only about 9000 were in mobilized 
army and air national guard units by the time the fighting ended 
there would be more than 58000 american casualties 97 would be 
guardsmen in those mobilized units 
in 1969 346 million men and women were on active duty in the 
armed forces and to maintain that strength the selective service 
had to draft 283586 individuals by contrast 389000 individuals 
were in the army national guard in 1969 and most of those units 
werent expanding 
waiting lists to get into the guard became a reality 
nationwide during the vietnam war but it happened at different 
times in different locations said maj david super a pentagon 
spokesman and specialist on guard and reserve issues 
some units in some states were hard to get into others 
werent super said 
the national guard was a legal alternative to the draft and 
many chose to pursue it said dan donohue the chief spokesman 
for the national guard bureau at the pentagon 
quayle the republican vice presidential candidate has said he 
decided to join the guard in 1969 so he could attend law school he 
has dismissed questions about whether he was trying to avoid combat 
in vietnam as a cheap shot 
i was willing and ready to serve my country quayle said 
i chose to serve my country in the national guard like millions 
of other people 
accoding to reports thursday quayle received a highlevel 
endorsement that eased his entry into the guard but its unclear 
whether he needed the help 
john s anderson a democrat and adjutant general of the indiana 
national guard until 1969 said the guard service had a waiting 
list john owens a republican and successor to anderson said 
indiana had vacancies galore in his units 
whether quayle needed help or not retired maj gen wendell c 
phillippi who was managing editor of the indianapolis news and 
worked for quayles grandfather eugene c pulliam said he 
contacted his multitude of friends within the guard when quayle 
applied the news reported 
i was asked about dan quayles abilities and capabilities and 
i recommended him very highly as i did with many other men 
phillippi told the news later phillippi said he made only one 
call on quayles behalf 
ironically quayle could have attended law school without 
worrying about vietnam or the guard six months after quayle 
enlisted congress approved a draft lottery system and in december 
1969 quayle received a number high enough 210 to push him 
outside the induction zone 
quayle was 22 in 1969 when he graduated from college and lost 
his college deferment from the draft he enlisted in the guard in 
indiana as a private on may 16 1969 and was trained first as a 
welder then a clerktypist and later as an information specialist 
with the 120th public affairs detachment of the indiana guard 
he received an honorable discharge on may 18 1975 
at the time of quayles enlistment as is the case now national 
guard units were subject to mobilization but the policy of the 
johnson and nixon administrations was to rely on activeduty forces 
to fight the war 
the only exceptions occurred in 1968 shortly after the seizure 
of the us spy ship pueblo four tactical fighter squadrons from 
the air national guard were mobilized in january and then in may 
20 army national guard units were called up including an army 
ranger company from the indiana guard 
only a portion of the mobilized units were sent to vietnam and 
all were demobilized by the end of 1969 
dan howard the pentagons chief spokesman said thursday the 
guard didnt look like too safe a place to me because those 
who were sent to vietnam saw combat and won 55 silver stars 681 
purple hearts one distinguished flying cross 16 distinguished 
service medals six legions of merit and over 1000 bronze stars 
i cant speak to the motives of any individual who volunteers 
for the guard who volunteers for active duty or whatever howard 
said im simply pointing out that the national guard served very 
honorably in vietnam 
