it is 1969 danny quayle is graduating from 
college and at 22 years old he is facing the shared dilemma of his 
generation what to do about vietnam hes lucky he has options 
nineteen years later his decision casts a shadow on the republican 
national convention 
the bush campaign wanted a baby boomer they got one and he 
carries the baggage of his generation this is not world war ii 
were talking about this is the vietnam war and millions of kids 
were trying to avoid it 
in quayles case he is wrestling with the image of a rich kid 
who chose law school over vietnam and traded on his family 
influence to make his dreams come true 
stripped of the veneer of 1988 presidential politics it comes 
down to this from john decamp of nebraska a vietnam veteran and 
former state senator who is among 2277 delegates voting on 
quayles vice presidential nomination 
back there in the 60s you had boys with money and influence 
who didnt want to go to vietnam finding a way to get into the 
national guard 
and then you had other boys without so much money and some of 
them didnt want to go to vietnam but they volunteered or got 
drafted and they went and some of them like me got shot at a lot 
and a great many of them just plain got shot and killed 
some 153300 wounded 58153 killed 
lets face it the question is whether a rich kids family got 
him into the guard when other people were getting drafted decamp 
said 
thats one question anyway 
quayle is being dogged by several 
most important for him is to explain why given the opportunity 
and even the inevitability of serving in the armed forces in 
vietnam he chose to pursue a national guard appointment instead 
on top of that he hails from the immensely wealthy and 
influential pulliam family and revelations that a prominent 
pulliam employee interceded with the guard on quayles behalf 
raises the silver spoon imagery that the republicans prefer to 
avoid 
thirdly quayle presents himself as extremely tough on national 
defense issues and is eager to provide a contrast to democrats who 
he criticizes as not tough enough that wont be easy if he is 
forced to defend his military record 
in 1969 quayle wanted to go to law school after graduating from 
depauw university but he was losing his student deferment from the 
draft and the war was at a peak without some sort of intervention 
quayle would surely be drafted and probably sent to vietnam 
so the grandson of publisher eugene pulliam went to talk to a 
former indiana national guard commander who worked as managing 
editor of a newspaper the indianapolis news owned by his family 
he got in the guard and he went to law school 
the same year 283586 young men were drafted into the armed 
services thousands more volunteered 
yet even among defenseminded republican activists everything 
is relative 
the thing thats important is he didnt go to canada said 
george w bush the nominees eldest son remember in 1968 
canada was an option he didnt go 
lets keep it in generational perspective 
indeed quayle was nothing special for his generation in 1969 
vietnam was not a popular war and it took a nonstop draft to keep 
up the military 
if he got in the national guard to dodge the vietnam war that 
may be an issue with some vietnam veterans i dont know said 
gop delegate noble cody of cookeville tenn but ill tell you 
one thing if i had a son that age and knowing what i do now about 
that war id do everything i could to keep him out of it 
from oregon delegation chairman tj bailey i am a vietnam 
veteran and i truly do not resent dan quayle for not having 
gone it is a way a number of my lifelong friends opted we have to 
examine the sanity and wisdom of people who resent him for not 
being shot at 
jerry prevo chairman of the alaska delegation said i guess 
the question still remains if he didnt join the guard would 
he have been drafted i think a lot of people who had the potential 
of getting out of going to vietnam used that potential that 
connection in those years 
that was 20 years ago people make mistakes when theyre 
young if we held up everything we did as young people none of us 
would be considered worthy of doing something for our country 
baby boomers will understand but the older generation may 
hold it against him said samuel atkins a watkinsville ga 
attorney and pat robertson supporter i see it as a bruise but 
not something that will injure the man permanently 
