<TEXT>
congress has approved a ban on 
production of nuclear weapons in brazil as part of the countrys 
new constitution which is expected to be finalized this year 
the twochamber congress doubling as a constituent assembly 
passed an amendment wednesday night specifying that all nuclear 
activity in national territory will only be allowed for peaceful 
ends 
but it rejected a clause that also would have banned the 
transportation storage or import of atomic weapons according to 
rep fabio feldman one of the amendments sponsors 
congress has been working since february 1987 on the new 
constituion brazils eighth 
brazil announced last year it had acquired uraniunenrichment 
technology which theoretically could give it the capability to 
build an atomic bomb 
the government repeatedly has said its nuclear energy program is 
only for peaceful ends but scientists and politicians have 
expressed concern about the destination of brazils enriched 
uranium 
brazil signed the tlatelolco treaty for nonproliferation of 
nuclear weapons in latin america but failed to ratify it 
the uranium is processed at a navy base in ipero in 
southeastern brazil where the navy is developing a reactor to 
power a nuclear submarine 
the project was kept semisecret during military rule here from 
1964 to 1985 its existence was officially revealed last year by 
president jose sarney a civilian who took office in 1985 
navy minister adm henrique saboia said in an interview thursday 
with the rio newspaper jornal do brasil that the ban doesnt affect 
the governments nuclear program 
the country already has taken on the obligation and the 
political decision not to build an atomic bomb he said 
brazil and argentina are the only south american countries with 
nuclear technology although argentina is more advanced 
brazil has one finished nuclear plant a 626kilowatt reactor in 
angra dos reis 90 miles southwest of rio the plant broke down 
frequently after it started working in 1985 and was dubbed 
lightning bug because it goes on and off 
in 1975 brazil signed an agreement with west germany for 
construction of up to eight more nuclear plants and transfer of 
technology but only two were started and work on them has all but 
stopped because of budget cuts 
</TEXT>
