<TEXT>
defense secretary frank c carlucci was 
expected to accept the finding of military investigators that human 
error led the uss vincennes to mistakenly shoot down an iranian 
airliner on july 3 pentagon sources said thursday 
president reagan earlier said the united states accepted 
responsibility for the tragedy and was willing to compensate the 
families of the 290 people killed in the incident although many 
members of congress have expressed reluctance to make such payments 
the announcement by carlucci expected as early as friday would 
mark the first public acknowledgement by the pentagon that the loss 
of life was caused by us servicemen rather than an equipment 
failure or specific action taken by iran 
the report implicitly ascribes some blame for the incident on 
iran however by noting that since the tragedy iran has changed 
the manner in which its civilian aircraft operate over the persian 
gulf climbing to 25000 feet while over land the sources said 
in the past iranian civilian aircraft including the a300 
airbus reached 25000 feet as they travelled over the gulf itself 
the sources speaking on condition of anonymity said military 
investigators found that radar operators aboard the vincennes 
misread data and mistakenly identified the airliner as hostile 
the error stemmed from pressure on members of a crew facing 
their first experience in combat as well as confusing behavior by 
the iranian airliner said the sources 
the report was expected to differ with comments made on the day 
of the tragedy by the chairman of the joint chiefs of staff adm 
willam crowe in finding that the plane was ascending or levelling 
off when it was hit and that it was in a civilian air corridor 
rather than outside it the sources said 
abc news said thursday evening that the report contradicts 
earlier pentagon claims that the airbus was putting out two 
identification signals one civilian and the other military 
instead it said the airliners transponder was transmitting only 
civilian signals and the military signals picked up by the 
vincennes came from a distant plane 
the report was expected to be consistent with crowes comment 
that the vincennes mistook the a300 airbus for an f14 fighter in 
part because the jet took off from a joint militarycivilian 
airfield minutes after the vincennes ended a surface engagement 
with iranian gunboats the sources said 
some mysteries remain why the airliner flew into a combat area 
and why it ignored repeated broadcast warnings by the vincennes 
in earlier versions of the report senior us military 
officials recommended that the servicemen responsible for the error 
not be punished it was not clear whether carlucci would take more 
drastic action according to the pentagon sources 
crowe who passed the report up the chain of command to 
carlucci recommended that the servicemen receive a nonpunitive 
letter of censure in their files a step that might damage their 
careers the sources said 
there was no indication that the pentagon would formally censure 
the commander of the vincennes capt will c rogers iii 
the investigation was carried out by rear adm william fogarty 
then given to gen george crist the commander of us forces in 
the persian gulf and then went to crowe for carlucci 
sources said that the report itself was about 70 pages long 
with an additional 1000 pages of documentation gathered by fogarty 
and his team 
the report is said to exonerate the sophisticated aegis radar 
and tracking system aboard the vincennes one of the most advanced 
ships in the navy 
