<TEXT>
never has the federal reserve board made an 
interestrate decision that wasnt controversial and its latest 
one a half percentage point increase to 65 percent in the 
discount rate continues the tradition 
perhaps the most controversial aspect of it was the timing 
right before a presidential election a sensitive time politically 
and economically and therefore a time when the fed usually does 
not jiggle the economic levers 
moreover it came just days after fed chairman alan greenspan 
extolled the economys health before congress offering little 
suggestion at the time that any quick action was needed on interest 
rates 
but as it was in the past and most likely will be in the 
future the most detailed controversy is coming not from politics 
but from the field of economics itself where seldom is heard a 
noncontroversial word 
among the disputes is whether the fed acted preemptively to 
rein in the economy before it began straining or after the fact 
that is merely to catch up with increases that already had 
occurred in other interest rates 
some say the feds constraint saved the economy others say it 
has given business a case of jitters that could curtail production 
some say it could pitch the economy headlong into its first 
official recession in six years 
if the intent of the discount rate increase was to settle down 
the market the fed missed the mark says dale stuard president 
of the national associaiton of home builders it overreacted to 
inflation he contends 
others such as wright investors service express a sense of 
confusion over the move observing that consumer spending already 
had slowed from an annual rate of 44 percent two years ago to just 
half that over the past year 
economic strength currently derives from business fixed 
investment and net exports they accounted for half the economic 
growth in the past year prompting wright to ask if these were not 
areas to be encouraged not stifled 
it was widely believed that such was in fact the feds policy 
and that it was being fulfilled that is the economy was in the 
process of shifting to manufacturing and exports from consumer 
goods and services 
a commonly expressed fear is that the fed conceivably might have 
focused undue attention on the inflation threat setting off a 
psychological reaction that could reinforce and accelerate the rise 
of interest rates 
as wright observes the inflation threat is not clearcut the 83 
percent factory utilization rate and the jobless rate of around 54 
percent are typical of levels that existed prior to 1970 a period 
when inflation was relatively tame 
not only had consumer spending been moderating but homebuying 
plans had turned mediocre a trend the national association of 
realtors termed a reaction to interest rate increases that already 
had taken place 
with such evidence of moderating pressure therefore why the 
sudden forceful and unexpected move by the fed pondering that 
question said stuard could produuce a good case of jitters that 
could push rates even higher 
paul havemann vice president of hsh associates of riverdale 
nj which calls itself the countrys largest publisher of 
mortgage information tends to agree 
the quick speed with which lenders raised their rates is 
something of an overreaction he said 
weve seen this happen before the stock market has trouble 
digesting two such events so they overreact that spills over into 
the credit markets and lenders closely tied to those markets 
are carried along 
the financial and economic people might continue to argue in 
this way never reaching a consensus on whether the fed was right 
or wrong but that is the nature of economics 
economists are used to an indefinite world it is the political 
people who want answers they will strive to understand the feds 
action but they might strive in vain 
the fed does not try to explain its actions 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

