<TEXT>
it was to have been the highlight of cardinal 
john oconnors peace pilgrimage to northern ireland an 
ecumenical service at the cathedral of st patrick where catholics 
and protestants historic antagonists in ulster would pray 
together for peace 
but when the new york archbishop and several hundred other 
american pilgrims arrived at the cathedral in armagh on july 25 
protestants were almost as scarce as the snakes patrick is reputed 
to have driven from the island centuries ago 
the only protestant on the altar was a retired church of ireland 
bishop and although several ministers sat with the congregation 
they asked that their names not be released 
on his flight back to new york however the cardinal said he 
was not surprised to explain he recalled his last visit to 
northern ireland in 1984 saying 
we had a dinner with a bunch of protestant clergy probably 20 
or 30 of us in all it was very amiable very constructive but 
before it was over one of them who appeared to be speaking for 
many said you know if my people even knew that i was having 
dinner with you they would disown me 
now i think enough of that continues so that those clergy 
who came to the service in armagh felt it was a little much at 
this time for them to go up into the sanctuary 
the armagh service showed that ulster is one of the few places 
in christendom where many protestants especially presbyterians 
still see ecumenism as a threat 
although oconnor had invested much hope in the pilgrimages 
three ecumenical services only the one in armagh occurred in an 
area where catholicprotestant relations are tense 
that however was where the protestant response was weakest 
possibly because the pilgrimage coincided with the anglican 
churchs lambeth conference in england which many protestant 
leaders attended as participants or observers possibly because of 
the pilgrimages distinctly catholic character 
whatever the excuse the fact remains that ecumenism remains a 
fighting word in northern ireland 
the provinces most famous politicianpreacher the rev ian 
paisley went to the vatican harlot city he terms it in 1963 
to protest the ecumenical council called by pope john xxiii and he 
marched illegally on belfast city hall to protest the lowering of 
the flag when the pope died 
when a presbyterian minister walked across the street five years 
ago to extend christmas greetings at the local catholic church he 
was nearly fired and his family was threatened paisleys 
followers accused him of ecumenical tendencies 
protestants like paisley regard ecumenism as a catholic plot to 
weaken protestant resolve and trick them into accepting the 
unification of the province which has a 21 protestant majority 
with the predominantly catholic irish republic to the south 
the pilgrimages other ecumenical services at the shrine of 
our lady of knock and at christ church dublin took place in the 
republic where interdenominational relations are relatively good 
the clergy here have no problems no problems at all dean 
james grant a local church of ireland minister said after the 
service at knock we get along here and if this is reported in 
the north it may help there but the north he allowed was 
something else again 
northern irelands troubles are really about economics and 
politics not religion but protestant has become shorthand for 
unionist one who wants ulster to remain part of great britain 
and catholic has become synonymous with nationalist one 
who wants a united ireland 
in dublin the pilgrims were offered a final reminder of how 
long protestants and catholics have been feuding in ireland when 
they attended mass at st marys procathedral 
asked what the term procathedral meant an oconnor aide 
said it was a temporary designation usually for a church that is 
being used while the cathedral is under construction or repair 
but st marys has been a procathedral since its construction 
in 1825 the original cathedral christ church was lost when the 
church of england broke with rome in the 16th century and the 
vatican has never revoked the cathedrals consecration 
so the catholic archbishop of dublin still sits in a 
procathedral four centuries after the protestant reformation in 
ireland thats only yesterday 
</TEXT>
