<TEXT>
a federal judge stunned the publishers of the 
detroit news and detroit free press by temporarily blocking todays 
scheduled merger of the newspapers business operations saying the 
plan would do irreparable harm 
us district judge joyce hens green issued an emergency order 
wednesday preventing the joint operating agreement between the 
newspapers from taking effect the joa will be postponed until at 
least sept 17 
former attorney general edwin meese iii approved the joa before 
leaving office last week both newspapers sought the agreement 
under an antitrust exemption of the newspaper preservation act 
william b schultz an attorney representing a group of 
advertisers and readers had argued that meese arbitrarily ignored 
an administrative law judges finding that neither daily qualified 
for the antitrust exemption as a failing newspaper 
green agreed with schultz contention saying consolidation 
of the free press and the news will harm their employees their 
advertisers and their customers as well besides being 
immediate these injuries will also be irreparable 
knightridder inc which owns the free press has said it will 
close the morning newspaper if the partial merger doesnt go 
through meaning the loss of 1500 jobs alvah chapman the 
companys chairman has said the free press sustained 100 million 
in operating losses since 1979 
i am very disappointed said free press publisher david 
lawrence it the decision seems to me to be so cruel to all the 
individuals involved 
the people of the free press have gone through 28 months of 
uncertainty and now they still dont know what will happen to them 
and this newspaper 
frank hawkins spokesman for miamibased knightridder said the 
parent company was studying its options 
