<TEXT>
the trial over suits stemming from the 
225 billion washington public power supply system bond default is 
scheduled to begin sept 7 but lawyers say jury selection and 
other factors could delay the start of testimony until sept 26 
in another development at a pretrial hearing here thursday it 
was announced that a law firm sued as a result of the biggest 
municipalbond default in history had settled out of court for an 
undisclosed amount 
us district judge william d browning has said jurors will not 
hear testimony on fridays chemical bank attorney thomas barr 
estimated that the fourdayaweek format plus jury selection 
opening arguments and jewish holiday observances could mean the 
first witness may not take the stand until sept 26 
more than 24000 bondholders and chemical bank a trustee for 
bondholders are suing the supply system for damages from the 1983 
default of bonds sold to build two nuclear power plants in western 
washington the plants never were completed 
melvin weiss an attorney for the plaintiffs announced during 
the proceeding that wood amp dawson a new york and washingtonbased 
law firm which served as bond counsel for wppss tentatively had 
agreed to an outofcourt settlement 
details were not immediately announced and could come friday or 
monday 
attorneys said outofcourt settlements not including the one 
announced thursday have totaled 276 million so far 
